  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Evelina A. S. Smith praises an article about &quot;woman&quot; in the Boston Quarterly Review. [The Boston Quarterly Review article is a January 1841 review of Lady Morgan&apos;s Woman and Her Master, probably by Orestes A. Brownson.] Evelina A. S. Smith tried to find material on Toussaint L&apos;Ouverture in the library. She refers to Harriet Martineau&apos;s book, The Hour and the Man. She asks if Nathaniel Colver has sold himself to the Devil. She knew him to be a wolf in sheep&apos;s clothing ever since she heard him discuss non-resistance principles with Henry C. Wright in Chardon Street Chapel. She reports on a joint meeting of the local male and female anti-slavery societies. Luther B. Lincoln and Dr. Willard take the Massachusetts Abolitionist and they have the impression that William Lloyd Garrison is &quot;entirely unworthy of respect.&quot; Evelina A. S. Smith thinks the New Organization is &quot;a curious compound of falsehood and deception, sanctity and holy zeal.&quot;</subfield>
